  "prompt": "Can cataracts affect younger people? What are the most common causes of it?",
  "response": "Yes, cataracts can affect younger people, although they are much more common in older adults. When cataracts occur in younger individuals, they are often referred to as \"early-onset\" or \"juvenile\" cataracts.\n\n**Causes of Cataracts in Younger People:**\n\nWhile age-related changes are the most common cause of cataracts overall, other factors are more likely to contribute to cataracts in younger individuals:\n\n*   **Genetic Factors/Heredity:** Some people are born with a predisposition to developing cataracts earlier in life due to inherited genes. These are called congenital cataracts.\n\n*   **Trauma/Eye Injury:** A blow to the eye, a penetrating injury, or any type of significant trauma can disrupt the lens and lead to cataract formation.\n\n*   **Certain Medical Conditions:** Diabetes is a significant risk factor for early-onset cataracts. Other conditions include:\n    *   Myotonic dystrophy\n    *   Galactosemia\n    *   Atopic dermatitis\n\n*   **Medications:** Long-term use of certain medications, particularly corticosteroids (like prednisone) can increase the risk of cataracts, even in younger people.\n\n*   **Radiation Exposure:** Exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun or other sources (like radiation therapy) can damage the lens and accelerate cataract development.\n\n*   **Eye Surgery:** Previous eye surgery for other conditions may, in some cases, increase the risk of cataract formation.\n\n*   **Congenital Cataracts:** These are cataracts present at birth or developing shortly after. They can be caused by genetic factors, infections during pregnancy (like rubella), or other developmental problems.\n\n*   **Lifestyle factors:** Studies have shown that obesity, smoking, and high alcohol consumption increase the risk of developing cataracts.\n\n**Important Note:** It's crucial to consult an ophthalmologist if you suspect you have cataracts at any age. They can diagnose the condition, determine the underlying cause (if possible), and recommend appropriate treatment options.\n",
